  "prompt": "Which mathematician solved the magic square problem?",
  "response": "The magic square problem, which involves arranging numbers in a square grid so that the sums of the numbers in each row, column, and both main diagonals are equal, has a long history and has been studied by many mathematicians over the centuries. \n\nOne of the earliest known magic squares is the 3x3 magic square, often attributed to the ancient Chinese. The Lo Shu square, a 3x3 magic square, is said to have been discovered by the legendary Emperor Yu around 2200 BCE.\n\nIn the Islamic world, mathematicians such as Thabit ibn Qurra (826\u2013901) and later Al-Buni (d. 1225) made significant contributions to the study of magic squares.\n\nIn Europe, the study of magic squares was advanced by mathematicians like Cornelius Agrippa (1486\u20131535) and later by Leonhard Euler (1707\u20131783), who made significant contributions to the theory of magic squares.\n\nTherefore, the magic square problem was not solved by a single mathematician but rather developed over time through the contributions of many scholars across different cultures and eras.",
